ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[_Mycobacterium bovis_ causes cattle tuberculosis and is very similar
to 2 other bacteria, _M. avium_ and _M. paratuberculosis_. On
testing, these may cross-react. However, PCR can distinguish between
them.
Bovine TB spreads among animals when they are closely commingled.
Coughing releases the bacteria into the air, possibly infecting
animals housed in the same building, or eating next to the one
coughing. Human tuberculosis is caused by a different bacterium, _M.
tuberculosis_, although _M. bovis_ can also infect humans. Milk
pasteurization kills the TB-causing bacteria. When pasteurization
standards were developed in the 1920's, _M. bovis_ and _M.
tuberculosis_ were considered the most resistant pathogens. - Mod.TG]
